-- Anglo American, Crucell, Enel, Xstrata: European Equity Preview
-- B y   T a r a   L a c h a p e l l e
-- 2010-11-01T00:54:44Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-11-01/anglo-american-crucell-enel-xstrata-european-equity-preview.html
The following companies’ shares may
be active in  European  trading. Stock symbols are in parentheses,
and prices are from the previous close.  The  Stoxx Europe 600 Index  advanced less than 0.1 percent
to 265.96. The  Stoxx 50 Index  slipped less than 0.1 percent to
2,542.76. The  Euro Stoxx 50 Index , a benchmark for nations using
the euro, fell less than 0.1 percent to 2,844.99.  Actividades de Construccion y Servicios SA  (ACS SM): The
Spanish construction company would keep  Hochtief AG  (HOT GR) as
a whole and is willing to guarantee this and make other
concessions in an investor agreement, Die Welt said, citing
Chief Executive Officer  Florentino Perez . ACS shares fell 12
cents, or 0.3 percent, to 37.71 euros.  Anglo American Plc  (AAL LN) and  Xstrata Plc  (XTA LN): The
mining companies’ Chilean Collahuasi unit restarted talks with
workers to try to avert a strike at the world’s fourth-largest
copper mine. Anglo gained 0.5 percent to 2,908 pence. Xstrata
slid 3.2 percent to 1,209.5 pence.  Assicurazioni Generali SpA  (G IM): Italy’s biggest insurer
plans to create an international management board and a new
position of country manager for Italy, La Stampa said, without
saying where it got the information. The stock rose 0.6 percent
to 15.75 euros.  Bayer AG  (BAYN GY): Germany’s biggest drugmaker said its
Xarelto blood thinner matched warfarin at preventing blood clots
in patients with an irregular heartbeat. The shares dropped 36
cents, or 0.7 percent, to 53.62 euros.   BHP Billiton Ltd.  (BLT LN): The mining company may increase
its $39 billion bid for Potash Corp. of Saskatchewan Inc. by 10
percent, the Sunday Times reported, citing people it didn’t
identify. The shares fell 0.3 percent to 2,213.5 pence.  Brederode SA  (BREB BB): The Belgian investment company
predicted a full-year profit and said its dividend will be as
much as last year’s at least. The shares rose 16 cents, or 0.9
percent, to 17.76 euros.  British Sky Broadcasting Group Plc  (BSY LN): News Corp.
will give the European Commission formal notification of its bid
for full ownership of British Sky Broadcasting Group this week,
the Sunday Times reported, without saying where it got the
information. The stock advanced less than 0.1 percent to 706.5
pence.  Crucell NV  (CRXL NA): The Dutch vaccine maker and Johnson &
Johnson said they are making progress on J&J’s planned $2.4
billion acquisition after Crucell disclosed a manufacturing
plant may be contaminated. Crucell slid 2.5 percent to 23.25
euros.  Enel SpA  (ENEL IM): Italy’s biggest utility said it raised
about 2.26 billion euros ($3.1 billion), less than its target,
in an initial public offering of its renewable energy unit. Enel
fixed the IPO price at 1.6 euros apiece. Enel rose 0.6 percent
to 4.10 euros.  Publicis Groupe SA  (PUB FP) Jean-Yves Naouri, chief
operations officer of the owner of the Saatchi & Saatchi and Leo
Burnett ad agencies, is a potential candidate to become the
company’s next chief executive officer, the Sunday Telegraph
said, citing an interview with current CEO Maurice Levy.
Publicis is open to possible acquisitions in China, India and
the digital market, Levy said. The shares declined 1 percent to
35.79 euros.  Sipef NV  (SIP BB): The plantation operator’s  Jabelmalux SA 
unit predicted an increase in fiscal-year recurring profit after
reporting higher production of palm oil, rubber and tea. Sipef
shares rose 10 cents, or 0.2 percent, to 57.30 euros.  SOS Corporacion Alimentaria SA  (SOS SM): Bunge Ltd. may
take a stake of as much as 30 percent in SOS by acquiring new
shares issued by the Spanish food company,  El Economista 
reported, citing comments by company officials at a shareholders
meeting. SOS shares fell 6 cents, or 3.4 percent, to 1.58 euros.  Technip SA  (TEC FP): The oil-services company doesn’t see
“major” acquisitions as a priority, Investir said, citing an
interview with Chief Executive Officer Thierry Pilenko. The
shares rose 1.9 percent to 60.39 euros.  Total SA  (FP FP): The French oil company is “confident”
it will continue to be a partner with Abu Dhabi in developing
the Persian Gulf emirate’s oil reserves after its current
production concession expires, Jean Luc Guiziou, Total’s vice
president for production in the Middle East, told reporters at a
conference in Abu Dhabi. The shares were almost unchanged at
39.045 euros.  UniCredit SpA  (UCG IM): Italy’s biggest lender isn’t
planning to reduce its “international presence,”  Roberto Nicastro , the bank’s new general manager, told Corriere della
Sera in an interview. UniCredit fell 1.32 percent to 1.87 euros.  Wuestenrot & Wuerttembergische AG (WUW GY): The financial
services company expects to retain its 50 cent dividend policy
even if earnings rise in coming years, Boersen-Zeitung reported.
The shares were unchanged at 19.01 euros.  To contact the reporter on this story:
